headline: AI leader Nvidia forecasts fourth-quarter revenue above estimates
summary:
STORY: Nvidia blew past Wall Street expectations after the closing bell on Wednesday, reporting stronger-than-expected quarterly profit and sales.

It also issued an upbeat revenue forecast... betting on booming demand for its AI chips from cloud providers, despite growing concerns about an AI bubble.

The report sent shares up four percent in after-hours trading... and it marks a defining moment for Wall Street.

Global markets look to Nvidia - which is the world's most valuable company - to determine whether investing billions of dollars in AI infrastructure expansion has resulted in towering valuations that potentially outpace fundamentals.

Ahead of the results, doubts had pushed Nvidia shares down nearly 8% in November, after a 1,200% surge in the past three years.

CEO Jensen Huang said sales of its Blackwell chips are quote, “off the charts,” and added, "The AI ecosystem is scaling fast — with more new foundation model makers, more AI startups, across more industries, and in more countries. AI is going everywhere, doing everything, all at once.”

Big Tech, among Nvidia's largest customers, has doubled down on spending to expand AI data centers and snatch the most advanced, pricey chips as it commits to multi-billion, multi-gigawatt build outs.

headline: Tech shares turbocharged by Nvidia's stellar earnings
summary: SINGAPORE (Reuters) -Shares of technology companies surged in Asia on Thursday, after bumper earnings from chipmaker Nvidia quelled investor fears of an AI bubble ​and breathed new life into a tech-led rally that has propelled global stock indexes to ‌record highs this year.  Nvidia on Wednesday surprised Wall Street with accelerating growth after several quarters of slowing sales and posted a fourth-‌quarter forecast that exceeded expectations, sending its shares up 5% in extended trading.  That provided a much-needed boost to Asian markets on Thursday, with shares of Taiwan's TSMC, the world's largest contract chipmaker and a major supplier of chips to Nvidia, jumping 3.6%.

headline: Stocks advance as Nvidia earnings light up global markets
summary:
STORY: Global stocks soared on Thursday, as investors cheered Nvidia's market-topping earnings.

Tech-heavy markets Japan, South Korea and Taiwan led the rally.

In South Korea, the benchmark KOSPI index was up 1.92%.

While Taiwan's chipmaker TSMC's stock was up 4.3%.

Japan’s benchmark Nikkei closed up 2.65%.

Markets in Japan were also assessing news that the prime minister's administration is reportedly preparing to pass a stimulus package.

It would be the country's biggest since the COVID-19 pandemic.

European shares also climbed on the opening.

The pan-European STOXX 600 was up nearly 1% in early deals.

Nvidia's blowout quarterly results, and a positive outlook came at a critical time for investors.

They've been rattled in recent weeks by fears of a global AI bubble.

The world's most valuable company said it expected fiscal fourth-quarter sales of $65 billion.

And Nvidia's third quarter sales rose 62%.

Later in the day, investor focus will shift to a long-awaited official U.S. jobs report.

It could sway expectations regarding the Federal Reserve's monetary policy verdict next month.
